{"id":"1501.06924","submitter":"Mark Bashkansky","authors":"J. Reintjes and Mark Bashkansky","title":"Considerations on an Optical Test of Popper's Experiment","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1080/09500340.2015.1063723","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.optics","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/publicdomain/","abstract":"  We present a detailed analysis of a previously published realization of\nPopper's experiment using entangled ghost imaging. Our analysis, which is based\non optical diffraction integrals, shows that, for the configuration previously\ndescribed, the transverse spread of an unmeasured particle (the signal photon\nhere) does not increase in inverse proportion to the width of its virtual\nconfinement when its entangled twin is confined in transverse dimension by a\nphysical slit. Rather we show that the spread of the unmeasured particle\ncarries no dependence on the width of its virtual confinement in the published\nconfiguration. Instead, it spreads geometrically at a rate determined by the\nnumerical aperture of the ghost imaging system. We further propose an\nalternative configuration for which the spread of the unmeasured particle does\nincrease in inverse proportion to the width of its virtual confinement. We\ndiscuss the relation of these results to the predictions of Popper.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Jan 2015 21:02:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-20"}
